WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:04.380
Mostly, I want you to do a gitignore at this point in the course.

00:04.380 --> 00:10.180
So git is obviously our source tracking for our project.

00:10.180 --> 00:13.480
And mostly, I just want you to make a gitignore file for stuff.

00:13.480 --> 00:18.540
This will really help out VS Code to be faster for just a bunch of stuff, because VS Code

00:18.540 --> 00:22.260
relies heavily on your gitignore being useful.

00:22.260 --> 00:24.100
And I just want you to, like, it's good.

00:24.100 --> 00:28.480
All of my projects, even if they're not making it to GitHub, I still have a habit of committing

00:28.480 --> 00:30.840
and tracking and all that kind of stuff.

00:30.840 --> 00:32.160
And most of it ends up on git.

00:32.160 --> 00:36.080
I have so much private garbage on GitHub anyway.

00:36.080 --> 00:43.240
So anyway, the first thing that you always ignore in your gitignore, especially if you're

00:43.240 --> 00:46.580
on your Mac, and especially if you're not on a Mac, is DSStore.

00:46.580 --> 00:48.440
This shows up in so many projects.

00:48.440 --> 00:49.440
It's hilarious.

00:49.440 --> 00:52.640
It's a file that's auto-generated by macOS.

00:53.640 --> 01:01.480
As far as I know, so if you just drag a file here, it's the positioning in the macOS window.

01:01.480 --> 01:03.080
And that's why it's in DSStore.

01:03.080 --> 01:08.720
It might be other stuff too, but anyway, that's why DSStore ends up in every file.

01:08.720 --> 01:13.560
Node modules, that should also be one that you immediately ignore, right?

01:13.560 --> 01:15.960
Because this is stuff that you don't want to check in, you just want to npm install

01:15.960 --> 01:16.960
it every single time.

01:16.960 --> 01:18.560
Do we have a dist in this?

01:18.560 --> 01:19.560
I can't remember.

01:19.560 --> 01:21.560
But we'll just copy what I have in here.

01:22.480 --> 01:24.280
Do we have a dot?

01:24.280 --> 01:25.280
I don't remember either.

01:25.280 --> 01:27.600
But .m files, you always want to ignore those.

01:27.600 --> 01:30.800
Coverage, we will have one of those.

01:30.800 --> 01:33.160
You can ignore the .vscode or not.

01:33.160 --> 01:34.160
That's up to you.

01:34.160 --> 01:35.640
I tend to ignore it.

01:35.640 --> 01:40.000
So the .vscode directory is like if you want to make configurations specifically for your

01:40.000 --> 01:44.640
project when you open it, it'll generate this .vscode directory.

01:44.640 --> 01:46.300
It's up to you if you want to check that in or not.

01:46.300 --> 01:51.360
If you think that's useful to share with your coworkers, then check it in.

01:52.160 --> 01:56.040
I can think of an example like it's a Python project, you want to make sure that everyone's

01:56.040 --> 01:59.200
using Pylance with your projects.

01:59.200 --> 02:04.160
You would have a .vscode directory that would tell their projects, please install Pylance

02:04.160 --> 02:07.040
for them.

02:07.040 --> 02:12.320
Up to you.

02:12.320 --> 02:16.880
If you need more instruction on this, Primogen definitely has a course.

02:16.880 --> 02:19.160
Everything you know about Git.

02:19.960 --> 02:20.960
And also Nina's.

02:20.960 --> 02:21.960
Nina's is also great too.

02:21.960 --> 02:23.960
Yeah, I hired Nina at Reddit.

02:23.960 --> 02:26.600
We worked together for a long time and then we worked together again at Microsoft.

02:26.600 --> 02:30.800
The last thing we'll do is run git init.

02:30.800 --> 02:33.000
It might yell at you.

02:33.000 --> 02:34.000
Oh no, it's fine.

02:34.000 --> 02:35.000
Okay.

